What is the measure, in degrees, of the supplement of an angle measuring $50$ degrees?
inference:
The supplement of an angle is the angle that, when added to the given angle, results in $180$ degrees.  Therefore, the supplement of a $50$-degree angle is $180 - 50 = 130$ degrees.

Final Answer: $\boxed{130}$ degrees. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: Two supplementary angles add up to 180 degrees. Thus the supplement of 50 degrees is $180-50=\boxed{130}$ degrees.
